assignments.description:
Objective
Create a game using Greenfoot and GitHub

Setup
See the Team Names provided. The first person in each team is the Team Leader.

1. Team Leader accepts the assignment and creates the team with that exact team name.

2. Everyone else joins the correct team.

3. Decide on a workflow. I strongly recommend this workflow:
- Create a new feature branch for each project change.
- Pull any changes from the remote onto your computer.
- Merge the main branch into your feature branch. Fix any merge conflicts in this step.
- Merge your feature branch back onto the main branch.


Criteria and Checklist
Your game should contain all of the following elements

Game and GamePlay
- A title screen and end screen
- Instructions or a tutorial or an intuitive user-friendly interface. The user should know what to do with minimal reading of instructions
- A scoring or achievement system
- Some way to motivate the player to continue playing. This could be from an engaging story, score system, increasing difficulty, score board, image rewards, powerups, or some other mechanic that you devise
- Sound and/or sound effects
- Some animation that shows the use of arrays

Source Code
- All classes are capitalized, and have good API descriptions
- Public methods should have javadoc API comments
- Good naming of variables, methods, classes
- Correct use of arrays
- Code should be organized, correctly formatted and easy to understand. If you feel your code is confusing or complex, include comments to help explain your coding intentions
- Your code should flow logically and be contained in classes and methods appropriately

Github
- You used Github to save and track your project progress
- You used the correct Github repository link provided
- There are no issues when I clone your files from the main branch of your respository
- Your Github history shows that you have regularly commited to the repository
- Your Readme.md file should summarize your project. What is your project about? How does someone get started playing it? Is there anything the teacher should know (e.g. cheat mode to get to the end screen)

Reflection
There will be a Google Form to fill out at the end of the course where you respond with a couple paragraphs to questions about your coding experience. What did you find challenging? What coding difficulty did you overcome when creating your game? 


Tips
If you are not that confident with your coding skills, consider creating an object-dodging or object-catching game similar to the tutorial.

Remake an existing game that you enjoy playing. Keep it simple. You can always add features to make it more complex.

Find and re-use existing images and code snippets. Give credit to the source in the readme file.

Use good coding technique. Your code should be logical, easy to follow and easy to understand. Add comments where appropriate. You should include Class and method documentation.

Make your game fun and challenging! Try increasing the difficulty as the player progresses through it. Perhaps increase the speed of objects or number of enemies.

You should be working on this project every day in class. Your commit history should show regular updates. If you feel you are finished before the deadline - you aren't. You can always add features, tweak your code or improve your project in some way.

Your main branch in your repository should compile and execute. You should be working on your test features on a separate branch. Follow a workflow that makes sense.

assignments.description:
Objectives
Collaborate on creating and improving the DodgeIt game.
Practice pull requests (PR), merging pull requests and becoming familiar with a good Github workflow.
Ensure each member has a chance to practice doing each of the steps below.

** PART 1 **
First...
1. Form a group of 2. Designate one person as the Team Leader.
2. The Team Leader accepts the assignment and creates the teams using your first names, ex team: Brinda Gauri

Next...
3. The rest of the team accepts the assignment and joins the correct team.
4. Re-make the DodgeIt game together. Decide together as a team who will do what. For example: create the Hero, create the enemy, create the game over.


Simple Workflow A (Recommended)
1. Make changes directly on the main branch.
2. Before pushing changes, pull the latest changes from remote (if they exist). Resolve any merge conflicts.
3. Push your changes.

Regular Workflow B (If you know what you're doing)
1. Create an issue in GitHub for each of the changes you want to make or add to the game.
2. Assign an issue to yourself. This is the one your team agreed that you would do.
3. Create a new branch, switch to that branch, and make changes to the project to fix the issue.
4. Create a Pull Request (PR) from your branch back to the main branch.
5. Have other team member review your Pull Request.

6. Other team member switches to the Pull Request. You should see the tab in Github Desktop.
Note: Before switching to your team member's pull request, you will either have to commit your unsaved work or Stash it. Stash means to save your changes locally without commiting - you can only have one stash.
7. Click on the Pull Request tab and choose the pull request that you want to review.
8. After switching to the PR, open the project and look at and discuss the changes that team member made.
9. Practice having the team member make more changes to the pull request.

10. Merge the change back onto the main branch.

** PART 2 **
1. Decide together as a team on 2 or 3 simple changes you want to make to the game. KEEP IT SIMPLE. This could be different images, speeds, adding new objects, etc. Communicate with your team so everyone understands what's going on.

2. Practice by making more changes together.

assignments.description:
1. Create a SuperKarel Sandbox.
You can create a Sandbox in CodeHS by clicking the 'Sandbox' tab at the top of your CodeHS page. Name your program 'Karel Maze Challenge' -> Click 'create program' -> Choose 'SuperKarel'.

2. Attach the sandbox link to this Google assignment.
In CodeHS click the 'Share' button at the top of the window. Copy the 'Show Code' link and attach it to this assignment by going to Google Classroom, select this assignment, choose 'Add or Create' -> 'Link', then past the link. (You will 'Turn In' this assignment later when it's complete).
*** Changing the Sandbox name will change the URL link. If you do this, RESUBMIT the new link ***

3. Create a 5 x 5 Maze World.
Do this by clicking on the drop-down box next to the bunny image. Choose 'add/edit worlds' and then make your maze using the editor that appears by adding walls to form a maze. Add one ball somewhere in the maze that represents the end of the maze. Name the world '5 x 5 Maze'. 

4. Create a 'Solution World' to the maze you just made.
Do this by clicking the 'Add Solution' button while in the world editor. Then move Karel to where the ball is and remove the ball. Save this solution world.

5. Write code that will solve any regular maze of ANY size. A regular maze is one where Karel can always follow a wall to eventually get to the ball. Ensure your code can solve the maze you created.

6. Create at least one more maze to test your code. Name your new maze(s) by its size, for example '7 x 8 Maze'. The maze does not need to be square, but make sure it is solvable.

7. Partner with someone. Create another maze based on one of your partners' mazes. Name it 'Other Maze'. Ensure that your code can solve their maze.

8. 'Turn In' this assignment in Google classroom when it's complete.

* Optional Challenge
9. Write code that will solve ANY maze of ANY size, even one where the ball may not be next to a wall. Put this code in a new Sandbox called 'Karel Maze Optional Challenge'. Create one or more irregular mazes to show that your code works. Attach a link to this sandbox when turning it in.

assignments.description:
Objective

Create a game in CodeHS.  Your goal is to have fun, learn new coding techniques, be challenged, and have a working program at the end to share with the class. 

Your final submission should reflect your best work from several weeks of design, development and testing. You should be working on this every period in class until the due date - there's always something you can fix or touch up.

Where to put your code
Create a Sandbox and name it Final Project. Attach the Show Code link to this Google Assignment.
If you are in a team:
- Make the Sandbox collaborative
- Make at least one other personal sandbox to experiment with ideas

Project Tips
• Self-assess your skill level and create an appropriate game that you can finish in the time remaining in the course
• Consider changing the screen size to match the type of game you're making.
• Consider using a Sandbox to test different features before adding to your project
• Consider remaking or taking elements from an existing game, either from CodeHS or another game you've played elsewhere
• Choose a game that you will have fun making and playing!
• Your CodeHS code history should show that you are working on the game on a regular, daily basis.
• Share your idea with me early in the development process. I can give helpful suggestions!

Code Documentation
Include a header comment at the top of your code with the following information:
•	Your name(s), date (month and year)
• A note to me, the teacher, regarding the objective of your game and any other info I might need when playing your game (perhaps cheat codes to get to all the parts of your game quickly)
•	Credit for sounds, images and code that you have used - provide the URL
•	Any known bugs/issues that you could not resolve

assignments.description:
Objective
Build a simple game in the given time limit.

Theme
"Simple and fun"
Focus on making it work and how to make it fun.

Rules
- Game Jam done ONLY DURING class.
- Use only what we have learned so far in this class up to 'Unit 11: Animation Challenges'. (No images, or sound, etc.)
- Your titlepage/firstpage shows your team Letter

DAY 1

1. The first person in the Team List is the team leader.

2. The team leader will create a shared sandbox and share its link with the rest of the group. From the sandbox, click Share -> Collaborate -> Enable Collaboration.

3. Each person creates their own individual sandbox to test their own code and functions. When ready, copy your code into the shared sandbox.

4. Brainstorm, discuss and decide on a simple game that your team will build. Keep it SIMPLE. Only use concepts that we have learned so far in this course so everyone in the group understands what's going on (Don't use downloaded images or sound - use only the drawing commands learned in class such as Circle, Rectangle, Line, etc).

5. Add a comment section at the top of the shared sandbox page that includes:
- Group member names
- Title of your game
- Any other relevant informtion

6. Implement (write the code) the game. Remember to follow conventions that you have practiced in this course such as:

- Having a main() function where the game begins.
- Using well-named and self-contained functions whenever possible.
- Keep global constants and variables to a minimum. When using global constants and variables, define them near the top of the page.

assignments.description:
Technology continues to change the world in profound ways. Did we ever think that cars could drive themselves and that computers could talk intelligently to us? Your task is to research a topic in technology and give a 10 minute TED talk.

A TED talk is meant to educate, inspire, challenge, amaze, and tell a story.  Describe why your topic is significant. Consider how you might inform, convince, inspire, or challenge your audience.

Notes
- Your talk should make the audience aware of a situation or issue without going into all the details. 

- You do NOT need to be an expert of the subject.

- Why is what you're discussing SIGNIFICANT?

- Watch a TED talk by clicking the link below to get a feel for the presentation format and style.


Your Task

1.	Sign up for your TED talk. Each group will present a different topic - no repeat of topics.

2. You will be assigned a random presentation date. There will be one presentation per day for the next few weeks.

3.	Prepare your talk. Practice your talk to minimize the use of notes!

4. You should use Google Slides or any Sharable presentation software that you can present from your own laptop/device. Slides should not contain too much text if any at all. They should be simple, clear and concise, perhaps just images. Attach your Slides link to this assignment today. You should Mark as Done on the day of your presentation.

5. Add the TED-Talk-Intro sound to your first slide. You will play this at the start of every talk and the audience will encourage you with lots of applause :D

6. When presenting, you should speak casually without referring to notes, like a TED talk. If you must, you can use your cellphone for notes, but should not be reading straight from it. As a general rule, in a 10 minute talk, you should be looking at your notes no more than 1 minute.

7. When presenting, you will control your own slides with your own laptop projected to the classroom screen. This will work for PC or Mac. This also works for iPad, but NOT chromebooks.

TED Talk Tips
•	Inspire, encourage, entertain, dazzle, amaze, and/or challenge your audience.
• Tell a story. Make it relatable to your audience.
•	Inform and raise a significant issue or idea without going into excessive detail. 
• Why is your talk significant?
•	Deliver the talk in a similar way as a TED Talk.
• Use simple explanations and examples.
• Use simple, large pictures and uncluttered slides. Your slides should have very little text.
• Do NOT read directly off your slides or notes.
• Think of the talk as a conversation with the audience.
• PRACTICE your talk beforehand.
• Be excited about your topic and have fun!

Summary
Attach your Google Slides TODAY
"Mark as done" this assignment on the day of your presentation.
Only one team member submits a slide link.

1. Create a SuperKarel Sandbox.
You can create a Sandbox in CodeHS by clicking the 'Sandbox' tab at the top of your CodeHS page. Name your program 'Karel Maze Challenge' -> Click 'create program' -> Choose 'SuperKarel'.

2. Attach the sandbox link to this Google assignment.
In CodeHS click the 'Share' button at the top of the window. Copy the 'Show Code' link and attach it to this assignment by going to Google Classroom, select this assignment, choose 'Add or Create' -> 'Link', then past the link. (You will 'Mark as Done' this assignment later when it's complete).
*** Changing the Sandbox name will change the URL link. If you do this, RESUBMIT the new link ***

3. Create a 5 x 5 Maze World.
Do this by clicking on the drop-down box next to the bunny image. Choose 'add/edit worlds' and then make your maze using the editor that appears by adding walls to form a maze. Add one ball somewhere in the maze that represents the end of the maze. Name the world '5 x 5 Maze'. 

4. Create a 'Solution World' to the maze you just made.
Do this by clicking the 'Add Solution' button while in the world editor. Then move Karel to where the ball is and remove the ball. Save this solution world.

5. Write code that will solve any regular maze of ANY size. A regular maze is one where Karel can always follow a wall to eventually get to the ball. Ensure your code can solve the maze you created.

6. Create at least one more maze to test your code. Name your new maze(s) by its size, for example '7 x 8 Maze'. The maze does not need to be square, but make sure it is solvable.

7. Partner with someone. Create another maze based on one of your partners' mazes. Name it 'Other Maze'. Ensure that your code can solve their maze.

8. 'Mark as Done' this assignment in Google Classroom when you are ready for me to mark it.

* Optional Challenge
9. Write code that will solve ANY maze of ANY size, even one where the ball may not be next to a wall. Put this code in a new Sandbox called 'Karel Maze Optional Challenge'. Create one or more irregular mazes to show that your code works. Attach a link to this sandbox when turning it in.

assignments.description:
Objective
Create a game using Greenfoot and GitHub

Setup
See the Team Names below. The first person in each team is the Team Leader.

1. Team Leader accepts the assignment and creates the team with that exact team name.

2. Everyone else joins the correct team.

3. Decide on a workflow. I strongly recommend this workflow:
- Create a new feature branch for each project change.
- Pull any changes from the remote onto your computer.
- Merge the main branch into your feature branch. Fix any merge conflicts in this step.
- Merge your feature branch back onto the main branch.


Criteria and Checklist
Your game should contain all of the following elements

Game and GamePlay
- A title screen and end screen
- Instructions or a tutorial or an intuitive user-friendly interface. The user should know what to do with minimal reading of instructions
- A scoring or achievement system
- Some way to motivate the player to continue playing. This could be from an engaging story, score system, increasing difficulty, score board, image rewards, powerups, or some other mechanic that you devise
- Sound and/or sound effects
- Some animation that shows the use of arrays

Source Code
- All classes are capitalized, and have good API descriptions
- Public methods should have javadoc API comments
- Good naming of variables, methods, classes
- Correct use of arrays
- Code should be organized, correctly formatted and easy to understand. If you feel your code is confusing or complex, include comments to help explain your coding intentions
- Your code should flow logically and be contained in classes and methods appropriately

Github
- You used Github to save and track your project progress
- You used the correct Github repository link provided
- There are no issues when I clone your files from the main branch of your respository
- Your Github history shows that you have regularly commited to the repository
- Your Readme.md file should summarize your project. What is your project about? How does someone get started playing it? Is there anything the teacher should know (e.g. cheat mode to get to the end screen)

Reflection
There will be a Google Form to fill out at the end of the course where you respond with a couple paragraphs to questions about your coding experience. What did you find challenging? What coding difficulty did you overcome when creating your game? 


Tips
If you are not that confident with your coding skills, consider creating an object-dodging or object-catching game similar to the tutorial.

Remake an existing game that you enjoy playing. Keep it simple. You can always add features to make it more complex.

Find and re-use existing images and code snippets. Give credit to the source in the readme file.

Use good coding technique. Your code should be logical, easy to follow and easy to understand. Add comments where appropriate. You should include Class and method documentation.

Make your game fun and challenging! Try increasing the difficulty as the player progresses through it. Perhaps increase the speed of objects or number of enemies.

You should be working on this project every day in class. Your commit history should show regular updates. If you feel you are finished before the deadline - you aren't. You can always add features, tweak your code or improve your project in some way.

Your main branch in your repository should compile and execute. You should be working on your test features on a separate branch. Follow a workflow that makes sense.

Objectives
Collaborate on creating and improving the DodgeIt game.
Practice pull requests (PR), merging pull requests and becoming familiar with a good Github workflow.
Ensure each member has a chance to practice doing each of the steps below.

** PART 1 **
First...
1. Form a group of 2. Designate one person as the Team Leader.
2. The Team Leader accepts the assignment and creates the teams using your first names, ex team: Brinda Gauri

Next...
3. The rest of the team accepts the assignment and joins the correct team.
4. Re-make the DodgeIt game together. Decide together as a team who will do what. For example: create the Hero, create the enemy, create the game over.


Simple Workflow A (Recommended)
1. Make changes directly on the main branch.
2. Before pushing changes, pull the latest changes from remote (if they exist). Resolve any merge conflicts.
3. Push your changes.

Regular Workflow B (If you know what you're doing)
1. Create an issue in GitHub for each of the changes you want to make or add to the game.
2. Assign an issue to yourself. This is the one your team agreed that you would do.
3. Create a new branch, switch to that branch, and make changes to the project to fix the issue.
4. Create a Pull Request (PR) from your branch back to the main branch.
5. Have other team member review your Pull Request.

6. Other team member switches to the Pull Request. You should see the tab in Github Desktop.
Note: Before switching to your team member's pull request, you will either have to commit your unsaved work or Stash it. Stash means to save your changes locally without commiting - you can only have one stash.
7. Click on the Pull Request tab and choose the pull request that you want to review.
8. After switching to the PR, open the project and look at and discuss the changes that team member made.
9. Practice having the team member make more changes to the pull request.

10. Merge the change back onto the main branch.

** PART 2 **
1. Decide together as a team on 2 or 3 simple changes you want to make to the game. KEEP IT SIMPLE. This could be different images, speeds, adding new objects, etc. Communicate with your team so everyone understands what's going on.

2. Practice by making more changes together.

Objective
Follow the video to learn how to use GitHub and Greenfoot to create a simple game.

Setup Requirements

1. Created a GitHub account
2. Downloaded and installed GitHub Desktop
3. Downloaded and installed Greenfoot

Notes
The focus of this tutorial is to become familiar with using GitHub to manage a coding project.
Create many small commits instead few large commits.
Experiment by changing actor images or modifying the code.
Experiment by practicing your Github skills such as branching.
Ensure your project's main branch can execute.

assignments.description:
1. Create a SuperKarel Sandbox.
You can create a Sandbox in CodeHS by clicking the 'Sandbox' tab at the top of your CodeHS page. Name your program 'Karel Maze Challenge' -> Click 'create program' -> Choose 'SuperKarel'.

2. Attach the sandbox link to this Google assignment.
In CodeHS click the 'Share' button at the top of the window. Copy the 'Show Code' link and attach it to this assignment by going to Google Classroom, select this assignment, choose 'Add or Create' -> 'Link', then past the link. (You will 'Turn In' this assignment later when it's complete).
*** Changing the Sandbox name will change the URL link. If you do this, RESUBMIT the new link ***

3. Create a 5 x 5 Maze World.
Do this by clicking on the drop-down box next to the bunny image. Choose 'add/edit worlds' and then make your maze using the editor that appears by adding walls to form a maze. Add one ball somewhere in the maze that represents the end of the maze. Name the world '5 x 5 Maze'. 

4. Create a 'Solution World' to the maze you just made.
Do this by clicking the 'Add Solution' button while in the world editor. Then move Karel to where the ball is and remove the ball. Save this solution world.

5. Write code that will solve any regular maze of ANY size. A regular maze is one where Karel can always follow a wall to eventually get to the ball. Ensure your code can solve the maze you created.

6. Create at least one more maze to test your code. Name your new maze(s) by its size, for example '7 x 8 Maze'. The maze does not need to be square, but make sure it is solvable.

7. Partner with someone. Create another maze based on one of your partners' mazes. Name it 'Other Maze'. Ensure that your code can solve their maze.

8. 'Turn In' this assignment in Google classroom when it's complete.

* Optional Challenge
9. Write code that will solve ANY maze of ANY size, even one where the ball may not be next to a wall. Put this code in a new Sandbox called 'Karel Maze Optional Challenge'. Create one or more irregular mazes to show that your code works. Attach a link to this sandbox when turning it in.
